           <h3 id="css">CSS</h3>
           <p>While this style guide won't go into detail about the specifics of the code it will explain the need to know basics of css styling within our app's code.</p>

           <h4>Philosophy</h4>
           <p>The main philosophy for our CSS is to re-use as much as possible. Very often in CSS we find ourselves repeating lines of code because of CSS's nature. Always try and structure elements so that they re-use mixins, variables etc. in the <code>.less</code> files such that the pre-processor does most of the work. We don't kill ourselves trying to do this, but we try and make a reasonable effort</p>

           <h4>LESS</h4>
           <p>Be mindful that we use <a href="http://lesscss.org/">LESS</a> when styling our code. So whenever we want to make a meaningful change to the styling we do so in the <code>.less</code> files. Channging <code>.css</code> file will not make a permanent change.</p>
           <p>When making changes to the <code>.less</code> we make use of variables &#38; mixins already in place or create our own. This dramatically increases the resuability of our code. Even for variables we may only use here or there it's still a good idea so that when the next person comes around they can easily spot the value, and the corersponding informative variable title describing what it does. At times it is useful to use these variables in such a way that there are relations between them.</p>
           <p>Our code heavily makes use of <code>.less</code> functions to facilitate wasteful repetition. Examples of this can be found in the <code>crossBrowser.less</code> file. Some important specific examples of where we use these are <code>.transition()</code>, <code>.transform()</code> and more importantly <code>.flex-display()</code>. Geting familiar with these (and more functions) is crucial for editing the code. If we create some code that may be good to reuse later we don't hesistate to make a funciton out of it and include it in a more general location</p>
           <p>Always pay attention to the imported files at the top of the <code>.less</code> files. If we don't understand where something is coming from - it's probably imported!</p>

           <h4>Important Files</h4>
           <p>All our main colors (as seen are above) are set in <code>~/yourpathto/roadmunk/app/client/assets/css/roadmunk.less</code>. We make any changes to our color palette here. We have a conventions of renaming the variables found in that file to something more context specific in other <code>.less</code> files</p>
           <p>Most of our re-usable function such as <code>.transition()</code>, <code>.transform()</code>  &#38; <code>.flex-display()</code> can be found in <code>~/yourpathto/roadmunk/app/client/assets/css/crossBrowser.less</code></p>
           <p>The more specific <code>.less</code> files (for each view) can be found in the path <code>~/yourpathto/roadmunk/app/client/views/roadmaps/templates</code></p>


